SIMPLE: pre
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pre
<hw>P⟦egrave⟧re</hw> <pr>(p⟦acir⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.,
fr. L. <ets>pater</ets>. See <er>Father</er>.]</ety> <def>Father; --
often used after French proper names to distinguish a father from his
son; <as>as, Dumas <ex>p⟦egrave⟧re</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peregal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pre-
<hw>Pre-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[L. <ets>prae</ets>, adv. & prep.,
before, akin to <ets>pro</ets>, and to E. <ets>for</ets>, prep.: cf. F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧-</ets>. See <er>Pro-</er>, and cf.
<er>Prior</er>.]</ety> <def>A prefix denoting <xex>priority</xex> (of
time, place, or rank); <as>as, <ex>precede</ex>, to go before;
<ex>pre</ex>cursor, a forerunner; <ex>pre</ex>fix, to fix or place
before</as>; <ex>pre</ex>⟦eum⟧minent eminent before or above others.
<ex>Pre-</ex> is sometimes used intensively, <as>as in
<ex>pre</ex>potent, very potent</as>.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>pr⟦ae⟧-</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preaccusation</ent>⟦br⟧
